{
  "response_text": "The system initializes with 90 animals per household. During the first 20 time steps, a steep reduction occurs, with animal numbers declining rapidly as households adjust to pasture conditions. This reduction continues through time step 37 but at progressively slower rates, reaching a minimum value of approximately 41 animals around time step 37.\n\nBetween time steps 33 and 43, the system enters a stabilization phase characterized by negligible directional change. Following time step 44, a sustained recovery period begins, lasting through the end of the simulation at time step 100. During this recovery, the aggregate mean increases gradually from the minimum to approximately 47.5 animals per household by the final time step.\n\nThe recovery phase exhibits considerable heterogeneity across simulation runs. While the mean trajectory shows consistent increase, individual runs diverge into distinct clusters by time step 100, with outcomes ranging from approximately 41 to 62 animals per household. This divergence becomes pronounced after time step 55, separating into multiple stable levels.\n\nThe rate of change varies markedly across the simulation timeline. The initial decline phase (0-20) shows the steepest reduction with a slope of -3.47, moderating to -0.96 (21-32) as the system approaches its minimum. The recovery phase begins with a slope of 0.31 (44-54), progressively decelerating to 0.002 by the final period (88-98) as the system approaches new equilibria.\n\nThis trajectory pattern reflects an initial overstocking scenario where the 90 animals per household exceed the sustainable carrying capacity of private pastures, leading to vegetation degradation and forced destocking. The minimum at time step 37 represents the nadir of this degradation. Subsequent recovery indicates adaptation through the three learning mechanisms (baseline rule-of-thumb, learning-by-doing, and social learning), with the divergence in final outcomes suggesting that different learning strategies produce measurably different long-term stocking capacities, with some households stabilizing at substantially higher levels than others despite identical starting conditions and rainfall variability."
}

